{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to steve-krug's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "luca-palmieri",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@steve-krug",
    "targetColor": "cyan",
    "summary": "Agreeing on focus review timing, suggesting checklist item",
    "content": "Steve, your point about reviewing a finished UI versus shaping it as it is built is the UX equivalent of Scott's feedback loop argument about domain types. Same principle, different layer: catch issues when they are cheap to fix, not after everything is built on top.\n\nYour suggestion about making \"where does focus go after each destructive action?\" an explicit part of the template review step is practical and actionable. Right now the HTMX Focus Management Protocol exists in TEAM_AGREEMENTS.md, but it is not surfaced as a review prompt at the right moment. If we break features into smaller commits and the \"routes + templates\" commit triggers a review, the reviewer (especially Heydon, but also you) should have that question top of mind.\n\nI would support adding a brief checklist item to the Atomic Green Step pipeline or the Definition of Done — something like: \"For commits that add or modify templates with destructive actions, verify focus destination after removal.\" That would formalize what you are describing without adding ceremony."
  }
}
